04683nam a22005895i 9780292733787DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927337877 a10.7560/7265052doi  a(DE-B1597)587679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLCO0100002bisacsh04a818/.541 aTrillin, Calvin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTrillin on Texas /cCalvin Trillin. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tBy Meat Alone -- tThe Dynasticks -- tMystery Money -- tBad Language -- tScouting Sleepers -- tConfessions of a Speechwriter/ And Especially to Pickens, S.C. -- tKnowing Johnny Jenkins -- tIf the Boot Fits ... -- tNew Cheerleaders -- tWhose Mines Are They? -- tNot Super-Outrageous -- tThree Texans in Six Lines -- tMaking Adjustments -- tPresidential Ups and Downs: Washington Pundits Take Their Analytical Skills to the Ranch -- tThe Life and Times of Joe Bob Briggs, So Far -- tOne Texan in Eight Lines -- tReformer -- tMolly Ivins, R.I.P. -- tCredits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Yes, I do have a Texas connection, but, as we say in the Midwest, where I grew up, not so's you'd know it." So Calvin Trillin introduces this collection of articles and poems about a place that turns up surprisingly often when he's ostensibly writing about something else. Whether reporting on the American scene for the New Yorker, penning comic verse and political commentary for the Nation, or writing his memoirs, Trillin has bumped into Texas again and again. He insists that "this has not been by design . . . there has simply been a lot going on in Texas." Astute readers will note, however, that Trillin's family immigrated to the United States through the port of Galveston, and, after reading this book, many will believe that the Lone Star State has somehow imprinted itself in the family's imagination. Trillin on Texas gathers some of Trillin's best writing on subjects near to his heart—politics, true crime, food, and rare books, among them—which also have a Texas connection. Indulging his penchant for making "snide and underhanded jokes about respectable public officials," he offers his signature sardonic take on the Bush dynasty and their tendency toward fractured syntax; a faux, but quite believable, LBJ speech; and wry portraits of assorted Texas county judges, small town sheriffs, and Houston immigration lawyers. Trillin takes us on a mouthwatering pilgrimage to the barbecue joint that Texas Monthly proclaimed the best in Texas and describes scouting for books with Larry McMurtry—who rejects all of his "sleepers." He tells the stories of two teenagers who dug up half a million dollars in an ice chest on a South Texas ranch and of rare book dealer Johnny Jenkins, who was found floating in the Colorado River with a bullet wound in the back of his head. And he recounts how redneck movie reviewer "Joe Bob Briggs" fueled a war between Dallas's daily newspapers and pays tribute to two courageous Texas women who spoke truth to power—Molly Ivins and Sissy Farenthold. Sure to entertain Texans and other folks alike, Trillin on Texas proves once again that Calvin Trillin is one of America's shrewdest observers and wittiest writers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72650540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292733787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292733787/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  